			<div class="longform post_img fullwidth">
			<img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/p20-Inuit-Dog-Sled-with-Three-Dogs-2048x875-1.jpg" alt="" class="entry_post"/>
		</div>
				<h1>Dogs Through the Ages: A Creative History of a Faithful Human Companion</h1>
		<h2>Jessica Poundstone Explores Canine Depictions in Art From Across the World</h2>
    <div class="inner">
		<div class="post_header_wrapper">
    		<div class="sponsored"><a href="https://www.chroniclebooks.com/products/museum-of-dogs" target="_blank" class="external">Via Chronicle Books</a></div>		</div>
				<div class="author_info" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
			<div class="author_name">By&nbsp;<a href="https://lithub.com/author/jessicapoundstone/" itemprop="url"><span itemprop="name">Jessica&nbsp;Poundstone</span></a></div>
			<div class="author_hr"><hr/></div>
			<div class="publish_date">May 5, 2025</div>
		</div>
		<div class="social_links">
						<a href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?via=lithub&text=Dogs+Through+the+Ages%3A+A+Creative+History+of+a+Faithful+Human+Companion&url=https%3A%2F%2Flithub.com%2Fdogs-through-the-ages-a-creative-history-of-a-faithful-human-companion%2F"><span class="social_twitter"></span></a>
			<a href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Flithub.com%2Fdogs-through-the-ages-a-creative-history-of-a-faithful-human-companion%2F&t=Dogs+Through+the+Ages%3A+A+Creative+History+of+a+Faithful+Human+Companion"><span class="social_facebook"></span></a>
					</div>
    <div class="inner">
    	<!-- Begin main content -->
    	<div class="inner_wrapper fullwidth">
    			
										<!-- Begin each blog post -->
						<div class="post_wrapper" style="padding-top:0;">
							<div class="post_inner_wrapper">
						    	<div class="post_wrapper_inner">
										<div class="inner_wrapper fullwidth">
								        
										<p>The following images are from<em> <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781797234243" class="external" target="_blank">Museum of Dogs: A Romp Through Art History for Dog People</a></em> by Jessica Poundstone.</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><script id="9b7a21a47fb44523b011db6d4f4cad23">(new Image()).src = 'https://capi.connatix.com/tr/si?token=546998bb-b9c0-4480-8c91-3e307220efff&cid=86b7c382-5e20-4129-84db-dea768f4d688';  cnx.cmd.push(function() {    cnx({      playerId: "546998bb-b9c0-4480-8c91-3e307220efff"    }).render("9b7a21a47fb44523b011db6d4f4cad23");  });</script></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<p><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="253060" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/dogs-through-the-ages-a-creative-history-of-a-faithful-human-companion/p13-japanese-three-young-dogs/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p13-Japanese-Three-Young-Dogs-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="2560,1790" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="p13-Japanese, Three Young Dogs" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p13-Japanese-Three-Young-Dogs-300x210.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p13-Japanese-Three-Young-Dogs-1240x867.jpg" class="wp-image-253060 size-large aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p13-Japanese-Three-Young-Dogs-1240x867.jpg" alt="" width="1240" height="867" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p13-Japanese-Three-Young-Dogs-1240x867.jpg 1240w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p13-Japanese-Three-Young-Dogs-300x210.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p13-Japanese-Three-Young-Dogs-768x537.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p13-Japanese-Three-Young-Dogs-60x42.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p13-Japanese-Three-Young-Dogs-1536x1074.jpg 1536w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p13-Japanese-Three-Young-Dogs-2048x1432.jpg 2048w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p13-Japanese-Three-Young-Dogs-50x35.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 1240px) 100vw, 1240px" /></p>
<p><strong>Three Young Dogs<br />
</strong><em>Attributed to Nakamura Hôchû, Japanese, 1826, color woodcut</em></p>
<p>If all the little Pokémon characters looked like these three, I would be so into it. Alas.</p>
<p>These portly puppies are part of a book published in 1826, most likely by an artist named Nakamura Hôchû. It contains twenty-six prints in which Nakamura revived a method of painting called mokkotsu, which means “boneless.” Yaaaaas.</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<p style="text-align: center;">*</p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="253061" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/dogs-through-the-ages-a-creative-history-of-a-faithful-human-companion/14-6-245/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p15-Egyptian-Sketch-Of-A-Dog-blue-bg-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="2133,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;Gustavo Camps&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;http:\/\/www.metmuseum.org\/art\/collection\/search\/548233&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1488296629&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/publicdomain\/zero\/1.0\/&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;14.6.245&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="14.6.245" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/548233&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p15-Egyptian-Sketch-Of-A-Dog-blue-bg-250x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p15-Egyptian-Sketch-Of-A-Dog-blue-bg-853x1024.jpg" class="wp-image-253061 size-large aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p15-Egyptian-Sketch-Of-A-Dog-blue-bg-853x1024.jpg" alt="" width="853" height="1024" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p15-Egyptian-Sketch-Of-A-Dog-blue-bg-853x1024.jpg 853w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p15-Egyptian-Sketch-Of-A-Dog-blue-bg-250x300.jpg 250w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p15-Egyptian-Sketch-Of-A-Dog-blue-bg-768x922.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p15-Egyptian-Sketch-Of-A-Dog-blue-bg-50x60.jpg 50w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p15-Egyptian-Sketch-Of-A-Dog-blue-bg-1280x1536.jpg 1280w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p15-Egyptian-Sketch-Of-A-Dog-blue-bg-1707x2048.jpg 1707w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p15-Egyptian-Sketch-Of-A-Dog-blue-bg-42x50.jpg 42w" sizes="(max-width: 853px) 100vw, 853px" /></p>
<p><strong>Sketch of a Dog<br />
</strong><em>Egyptian, 1295–1070 BC, limestone</em></p>
<p>Egyptians used chips of limestone with animal images like this one as illustrations when they told stories and jokes. This pup was definitely up to something extremely suspicious and/or goofy in this story.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">*</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="253062" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/dogs-through-the-ages-a-creative-history-of-a-faithful-human-companion/eee-041/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p17-British-Box-With-Dog-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="2560,1921" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;PHOTO&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;eee 041&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;eee 041&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="eee 041" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;eee 041&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p17-British-Box-With-Dog-300x225.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p17-British-Box-With-Dog-1240x930.jpg" class="wp-image-253062 size-large aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p17-British-Box-With-Dog-1240x930.jpg" alt="" width="1240" height="930" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p17-British-Box-With-Dog-1240x930.jpg 1240w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p17-British-Box-With-Dog-300x225.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p17-British-Box-With-Dog-768x576.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p17-British-Box-With-Dog-60x45.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p17-British-Box-With-Dog-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p17-British-Box-With-Dog-2048x1537.jpg 2048w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p17-British-Box-With-Dog-50x38.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 1240px) 100vw, 1240px" /></p>
<p><strong>Box<br />
</strong><em>British, 19th century, enamel on copper</em></p>
<p>If you had been alive in eighteenth-century England, you might have been gifted a small box like this one with candy in it.</p>
<p>What kind of candy, you ask?</p>
<p>Well, with sugar production up (which drove sugar prices down—see, I was paying attention in econ), Victorian-era folks went a little bonkers inventing new confections, including pear drops, sherbet lemons, cough candy, aniseed twists, marshmallows, candy floss, and fruit gums.</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<p>One of each, please (okay, maybe I can do without the cough candy): Put them all in a derpy-dog bonbon box and I will love you forever.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">*</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="253063" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/dogs-through-the-ages-a-creative-history-of-a-faithful-human-companion/1929-8-194_1-tif/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p19-European-Dog-Pendant-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="2019,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;19&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;Smithsonian American Art Museum&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;Hasselblad CF-39MS - Hasselblad H2&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;Direct capture&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1443789567&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;This image was obtained from the Smithsonian American Art Museum. The image or its contents may be protected by international co&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;120&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;50&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;3&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;1929.8.194_1.tif&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="1929.8.194_1.tif" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Direct capture&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p19-European-Dog-Pendant-237x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p19-European-Dog-Pendant-807x1024.jpg" class="wp-image-253063 size-large aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p19-European-Dog-Pendant-807x1024.jpg" alt="" width="807" height="1024" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p19-European-Dog-Pendant-807x1024.jpg 807w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p19-European-Dog-Pendant-237x300.jpg 237w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p19-European-Dog-Pendant-768x974.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p19-European-Dog-Pendant-47x60.jpg 47w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p19-European-Dog-Pendant-1211x1536.jpg 1211w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p19-European-Dog-Pendant-1615x2048.jpg 1615w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p19-European-Dog-Pendant-39x50.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p19-European-Dog-Pendant-scaled.jpg 2019w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 807px) 100vw, 807px" /></p>
<p><strong>Dog Pendant<br />
</strong><em>European, 1575–1600, gold, rubies, pearls, and enamel</em></p>
<p>This pendant was one of many made in the late 1500s where the jeweler used the irregular shape of a pearl as the inspiration for the body of the work. I’m not sure who would have wanted to wear this pendant, but I am quite sure that I would like to have met them.</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<p style="text-align: center;">*</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="253064" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/dogs-through-the-ages-a-creative-history-of-a-faithful-human-companion/p20-inuit-dog-sled-with-three-dogs/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p20-Inuit-Dog-Sled-with-Three-Dogs-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="2560,1093" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;Minneapolis Institute of Art&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;This media may be subject to copyright. Rights assessment is your responsibility.&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="p20-Inuit, Dog Sled with Three Dogs" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p20-Inuit-Dog-Sled-with-Three-Dogs-300x128.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p20-Inuit-Dog-Sled-with-Three-Dogs-1240x530.jpg" class="wp-image-253064 size-large aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p20-Inuit-Dog-Sled-with-Three-Dogs-1240x530.jpg" alt="" width="1240" height="530" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p20-Inuit-Dog-Sled-with-Three-Dogs-1240x530.jpg 1240w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p20-Inuit-Dog-Sled-with-Three-Dogs-300x128.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p20-Inuit-Dog-Sled-with-Three-Dogs-768x328.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p20-Inuit-Dog-Sled-with-Three-Dogs-60x26.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p20-Inuit-Dog-Sled-with-Three-Dogs-1536x656.jpg 1536w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p20-Inuit-Dog-Sled-with-Three-Dogs-2048x875.jpg 2048w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p20-Inuit-Dog-Sled-with-Three-Dogs-50x21.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1240px) 100vw, 1240px" /></p>
<p><strong>Dog Sled with Three Dogs<br />
</strong><em>Inuit, 19th century, walrus ivory, pigment, string, and animal hide</em></p>
<p>Inuit carvers believed that amulets had the power to lead hunters to the animals they needed for survival. The detail here is stunning, down to the leather harnesses on the three sled dogs.</p>
<p>Although women weren’t typically included in hunting parties, there is a female figure in this work—exciting to see!</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">*</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="253065" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/dogs-through-the-ages-a-creative-history-of-a-faithful-human-companion/p23-dutch-sleeping-dog/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p23-Dutch-Sleeping-Dog-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="2560,1928" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="p23-Dutch, Sleeping Dog" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p23-Dutch-Sleeping-Dog-300x226.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p23-Dutch-Sleeping-Dog-1240x934.jpg" class="wp-image-253065 size-large aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p23-Dutch-Sleeping-Dog-1240x934.jpg" alt="" width="1240" height="934" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p23-Dutch-Sleeping-Dog-1240x934.jpg 1240w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p23-Dutch-Sleeping-Dog-300x226.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p23-Dutch-Sleeping-Dog-768x578.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p23-Dutch-Sleeping-Dog-60x45.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p23-Dutch-Sleeping-Dog-1536x1157.jpg 1536w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p23-Dutch-Sleeping-Dog-2048x1542.jpg 2048w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p23-Dutch-Sleeping-Dog-50x38.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1240px) 100vw, 1240px" /></p>
<p><strong>Sleeping Dog<br />
</strong><em>Bertha van Hasselt, Dutch, 1930, lithograph on paper</em></p>
<p>Did you know—because I sure did not—that from 1912 to 1948 the Olympics included art competitions in five categories: architecture, literature, music, painting, and sculpture? For works with sports-related themes? Like what?! Bring it back!</p>
<p>Dutch painter and printmaker Bernardina Johanna Roberta (a.k.a. Bertha) van Hasselt entered her work at the 1928 Summer Olympics in Amsterdam. Sadly, she did not medal, but I would definitely have given her the gold for this absolutely delightful Great Dane.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">*</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="253066" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/dogs-through-the-ages-a-creative-history-of-a-faithful-human-companion/poudrier-caniches-titre-principal/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p25-French-Drawing-For-Makeup-Compact-With-Poodles-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="1889,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;16&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;Boucheron | Strauss, Allard et M&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;Azentis \/ P65+&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;Boucheron, Poudrier caniches (Titre principal), , Graphite et encre au recto, gouache au verso sur calque embouti Boucheron Paris mod\u00e8le d\u00e9pos\u00e9. Petit Palais, Mus\u00e9e des Beaux-Arts de la Ville de Paris.&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1305824648&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;CC0 Paris Mus\u00e9es \/ Petit Palais, mus\u00e9e des Beaux-Arts de la Ville de Paris&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;55&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;100&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.008&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Poudrier caniches (Titre principal)&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Poudrier caniches (Titre principal)" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Boucheron, Poudrier caniches (Titre principal), , Graphite et encre au recto, gouache au verso sur calque embouti Boucheron Paris modèle déposé. Petit Palais, Musée des Beaux-Arts de la Ville de Paris.&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p25-French-Drawing-For-Makeup-Compact-With-Poodles-221x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p25-French-Drawing-For-Makeup-Compact-With-Poodles-756x1024.jpg" class="wp-image-253066 size-large aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p25-French-Drawing-For-Makeup-Compact-With-Poodles-756x1024.jpg" alt="" width="756" height="1024" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p25-French-Drawing-For-Makeup-Compact-With-Poodles-756x1024.jpg 756w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p25-French-Drawing-For-Makeup-Compact-With-Poodles-221x300.jpg 221w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p25-French-Drawing-For-Makeup-Compact-With-Poodles-768x1041.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p25-French-Drawing-For-Makeup-Compact-With-Poodles-44x60.jpg 44w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p25-French-Drawing-For-Makeup-Compact-With-Poodles-1133x1536.jpg 1133w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p25-French-Drawing-For-Makeup-Compact-With-Poodles-1511x2048.jpg 1511w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p25-French-Drawing-For-Makeup-Compact-With-Poodles-37x50.jpg 37w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p25-French-Drawing-For-Makeup-Compact-With-Poodles-scaled.jpg 1889w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 756px) 100vw, 756px" /></p>
<p><strong>Poodle Powder Box<br />
</strong><em>French, 1940, ink and gouache on tracing paper</em></p>
<p>In 1940, the extremely posh jewelry purveyors Maison Boucheron hired the design firm of Strauss, Allard, and Meyer to come up with ideas for makeup compacts. Tragically, this design does not appear to have been manufactured. But the cases that were made—from pure gold and often featuring precious jewels and intricate, lacy cutouts on the lid—are worth looking up.</p>
<p>Maison Boucheron is still in operation today. Perhaps if we all write to them and ask very nicely they might produce this design for us? It’s worth a try.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">*</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="253067" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/dogs-through-the-ages-a-creative-history-of-a-faithful-human-companion/69-176/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p27-Russian-Sculpture-Of-A-Bolognese-Terrier-tallpeach.jpg" data-orig-size="750,1200" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;http:\/\/www.metmuseum.org\/art\/collection\/search\/205132&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/publicdomain\/zero\/1.0\/&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;69.176&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="69.176" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/205132&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p27-Russian-Sculpture-Of-A-Bolognese-Terrier-tallpeach-188x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p27-Russian-Sculpture-Of-A-Bolognese-Terrier-tallpeach-640x1024.jpg" class="wp-image-253067 size-large aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p27-Russian-Sculpture-Of-A-Bolognese-Terrier-tallpeach-640x1024.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="1024" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p27-Russian-Sculpture-Of-A-Bolognese-Terrier-tallpeach-640x1024.jpg 640w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p27-Russian-Sculpture-Of-A-Bolognese-Terrier-tallpeach-188x300.jpg 188w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p27-Russian-Sculpture-Of-A-Bolognese-Terrier-tallpeach-38x60.jpg 38w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p27-Russian-Sculpture-Of-A-Bolognese-Terrier-tallpeach-31x50.jpg 31w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/p27-Russian-Sculpture-Of-A-Bolognese-Terrier-tallpeach.jpg 750w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></p>
<p><strong>Bolognese Terrier<br />
</strong><em>Russian, 1811–1850, porcelain</em></p>
<p>Porcelain was a big deal in Russia during the 1800s, due in part to its promotion by the leaders of the splendidly named Imperial Society for the Encouragement of the Arts in St. Petersburg. Any organization that encourages the creation of something as majestic as this Bolognese terrier has to be doing something at least a little bit right.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">__________________________________</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="253058" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/dogs-through-the-ages-a-creative-history-of-a-faithful-human-companion/museum-of-dogs-front-cover/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/Museum-of-Dogs-front-cover.jpg" data-orig-size="1350,1800" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Museum of Dogs-front cover" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/Museum-of-Dogs-front-cover-225x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/Museum-of-Dogs-front-cover-768x1024.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-253058" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/Museum-of-Dogs-front-cover-225x300.jpg" alt="" width="225" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/Museum-of-Dogs-front-cover-225x300.jpg 225w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/Museum-of-Dogs-front-cover-768x1024.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/Museum-of-Dogs-front-cover-45x60.jpg 45w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/Museum-of-Dogs-front-cover-1152x1536.jpg 1152w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/Museum-of-Dogs-front-cover-38x50.jpg 38w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/Museum-of-Dogs-front-cover.jpg 1350w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 225px) 100vw, 225px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Excerpted from</em> <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781797234243" class="external" target="_blank">Museum of Dogs: A Romp Through Art History for Dog People</a> <em>by Jessica Poundstone. Copyright © 2025. Published by Chronicle Books.</em></p>
										
																				
																		
										<div class="post_wrapper author">
											<div id="about_the_author">
												<div class="gravatar"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/jessicapoundstone/"><img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/Jessica-Poundstone-author-photo-100x100.png" width="100" height="100" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/Jessica-Poundstone-author-photo-300x300.png 2x" alt="Jessica Poundstone" class="avatar avatar-100 wp-user-avatar wp-user-avatar-100 alignnone photo" /></a></div>
												<div class="description author withsidebar">
													<h6><a href="https://lithub.com/author/jessicapoundstone/">Jessica Poundstone</a></h6>
													Jessica Poundstone is an artist, designer and writer living in Portland, Oregon with her family and her precious pug/chihuahua (aka chug) mix, Stanley. See more of Jessica’s work at www.jessicapoundstone.com and on Instagram @jessicapoundstone																										<div class="website">
						    							<i class="fa fa-link"></i>
							    						<a href="https://www.jessicapoundstone.com" target="_blank" class="external">https://www.jessicapoundstone.com</a>
